\begin_layout Subsection*
The Predictor Initial Guess
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the initial guess for the nonlinear system of the DG predictor be 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}^{0}}=\theta_{k}\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2010"

\end_inset

 this is taken to be the WENO reconstruction, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}^{0}}\left(\chi,\tau\right)=\boldsymbol{w}\left(\chi\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hidalgo2011"

\end_inset

, a more sophisticated initial guess is used for systems of the form 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonConservativeSystem"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B=0$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the Gauss-Legendre abscissae on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tau_{0},\ldots,\tau_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau_{j}=\tau_{j+1}-\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}^{0}}=\psi_{i}\left(\chi\right)\psi_{j}\left(\tau\right)\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}} & =\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}-\Delta\tau_{j}\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)}{\partial x}+\frac{\Delta\tau_{j}}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}}\right)+\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)\right)\\
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i0}} & =\boldsymbol{w_{i}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit second order Taylor method is used to solve the flux term, combined
 with a second order Crank–Nicholson scheme for the stiff source term.
 In this study, this method was adapted to deal with the non-conservative
 terms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}} & =\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}-\Delta\tau_{j}M\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial\psi_{k}}{\partial\chi}\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{kj}}\right)+\frac{\Delta\tau_{j}}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}}\right)+\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)\right)\\
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i0}} & =\boldsymbol{w_{i}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonConservativeSystem2"

\end_inset

.
 The Taylor method for the flux term is no longer necessary.
 The system was solved by a Newton method to deal with the stiff source
 term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the more sophisticated initial guess would reduce overall
 computation times on some problems, owing to a faster convergence of the
 DG calculation.
 On other problems, the total computation time would increase, owing to
 the added cost of calculating the initial guess.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2008,Dumbser2008a,Dumbser2009a"

\end_inset

 for other choices for the initial guess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Finite Volume Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the formulation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2014"

\end_inset

, integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonConservativeSystem"

\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{n},t_{n+1}\right]\times C_{i}$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n+1}}=\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}+\Delta t_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{S_{i}^{n}}-\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n}}\right)-\frac{\Delta t_{n}}{\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{D_{i+1}^{n}}-\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta x}\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{i+1}}\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t_{n}\right)dx\\
\boldsymbol{S_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}\Delta x}\int_{t_{n}}^{t_{n+1}}\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{i+1}}\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)dxdt\\
\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}\Delta x}\int_{t_{n}}^{t_{n+1}}\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{i+1}}B\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial x}dxdt\\
\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}}\int_{t_{n}}^{t_{n+1}}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\left(x_{i},t\right),\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\left(x_{i},t\right)\right)dt
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q^{-},Q^{+}}$
\end_inset

 are the left and right extrapolated states at the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 boundary.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S_{i}^{n}},\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n}},\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n}}$
\end_inset

 are calculated using an 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

-point Gauss-Legendre quadrature, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, as defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:The Discontinuous Galerkin Predictor"

\end_inset

, is a diagonalisable matrix with decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $M=R\Lambda R^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are the right eigenvectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
 Define the following matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|M\right|=R\left|\Lambda\right|R^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these definitions, the interface terms arising in the FV formula have
 the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}},\boldsymbol{q^{+}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)+\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}\right)+\hat{B}\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)-\hat{M}\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

 is chosen to either correspond to a Rusanov/Lax-Friedrichs flux 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}=\max\left(\max\left|\Lambda\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)\right|,\max\left|\Lambda\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}\right)\right|\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or a simplified Osher–Solomon flux 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2011,Dumbser2011a"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}=\int_{0}^{1}\left|M\left(\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{q^{-}}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)\right)\right|dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 takes the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}=\int_{0}^{1}B\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q}^{-}\right)\right)dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the Osher-Solomon flux would often produce slightly less
 diffusive results, but that it was more computationally expensive, and
 also had a greater tendency to introduce numerical artefacts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Time Step and Boundary Conditions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Time Step and Boundary Conditions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be the set of eigenvalues of the HPR system evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{cfl}<1$
\end_inset

 is a constant (usually taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.9$
\end_inset

, unless the problem being simulated is particularly demanding, requiring
 a lower value).
 A semi-analytic form for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Eigenstructure of the HPR Model"

\end_inset

.
 The eigenvalues determine the speed of propagation of information in the
 solution to the Riemann Problem at the cell interfaces, and the time step
 is chosen to ensure that the characteristics do not enter into other cells
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta t_{n}=\frac{C_{cfl}\cdot\Delta x}{\max_{i}\left|\Lambda_{i}^{n}\right|}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transmissive boundary conditions (allowing material and heat to pass through)
 are implemented by setting the state variables in the boundary cells to
 the same value as their non-boundary neighbours.
 Reflective boundary conditions are implemented in the same way, except
 that the directions of the velocity and thermal impulse vectors in the
 boundary cells are reversed.
 Where fixed temperature boundary conditions are used, reflective boundary
 conditions are first imposed, after which the pressure is altered so that
 the boundary cell has the desired temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{fixed}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=\rho\left(\gamma-1\right)c_{v}T_{fixed}-p_{\infty}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where a fixed boundary heat flux 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is specified, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{q\cdot\Delta t}{\Delta x}$
\end_inset

 is added to the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho E$
\end_inset

 in the boundary cell.
 It may be appropriate to also fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

 in the boundary cell in accordance with the specified heat flux (as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}=\alpha^{2}T\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

), but this was not done here, as no analogous procedure was undertaken
 in the studies with which this study compares its results.
 The effect of this measure is a potential area of further research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Operator Splitting
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Operator-Splitting"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although not applicable to the full HPR system in the form given here, the
 operator splitting method is used when solving the reduced HPR system in
 slow cookoff simulations.
 Take the following conservative hyperbolic system with sources:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)}{\partial x}=\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time step 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q^{n}}$
\end_inset

 as initial data, the homogeneous system is evolved by time step 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 to produce an intermediate state 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{Q}}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)}{\partial x}=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exist many methods with which to accomplish this (see Toro for an
 overview 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

).
 In this study, the following scheme is used:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\boldsymbol{Q_{i}}}^{n+1}=\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}+\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}}-\boldsymbol{F_{i-\frac{1}{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $i+\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 is used to denote the value between cells 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}}$
\end_inset

 was chosen to be the first-order First-Order Centred flux of Toro 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "toro1996glimm"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{LF}}+\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{RI}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{LF}}$
\end_inset

 is the Lax-Friedrichs flux:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{LF}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i}}\right)+\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i+1}}\right)\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i}}-\boldsymbol{Q_{i+1}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{RI}}$
\end_inset

 is the Richtmyer flux 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ritchtmyer1957difference"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{RI}} & =\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i}}+\boldsymbol{Q_{i+1}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i}}\right)-\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i+1}}\right)\right)\\
\boldsymbol{F_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{RI}} & =\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q_{i+\frac{1}{2}}^{RI}}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n+1}}}$
\end_inset

 is used as initial data to the following system of ODEs.
 
\end_layout

